# Esophagus

> The esophagus is a **muscular tube ~25 cm long** connecting the pharynx to the [[Stomach]], passing through the neck, posterior mediastinum, and diaphragm. It has **no mesentery and no serosal layer** — crucial for surgical anastomosis leaks.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- Begins at: C6 ([[Cervical Vertebrae]]) — cricoid cartilage level
- Passes through: posterior mediastinum alongside [[Thoracic Vertebrae]]
- Pierces diaphragm at: T10 (oesophageal hiatus); relation to [[Ribs]]
- Joins [[Stomach]] at: gastro-oesophageal (GO) junction (T11)
- Posterior to: trachea, left main bronchus, [[Heart]] (LA)
- Blood supply: inferior thyroid artery (cervical), oesophageal branches of descending aorta ([[Aorta]]), left gastric artery ([[Celiac Trunk]])
- Venous drainage: azygos vein → [[Superior Vena Cava]] (upper); left gastric vein → [[Portal System]] (lower) — **portosystemic anastomosis**

## 🗂️ Key Information

| Property | Detail |
|----------|--------|
| Length | ~25 cm (15 cm from incisors to start, 40 cm to stomach) |
| Muscle type | Upper 1/3: striated; Middle 1/3: mixed; Lower 1/3: smooth |
| Layers | Mucosa → submucosa → muscularis propria → adventitia (NO serosa) |
| Innervation | Vagus nerve (CN X) + sympathetic chain |

## 🔑 Three Anatomical Narrowings (Sites of Foreign Body / Cancer)
1. **Cricopharyngeal sphincter** (C6) — upper oesophageal sphincter (UOS); 15 cm from incisors
2. **Aortic arch + left main bronchus** crossing — 25 cm from incisors
3. **Oesophageal hiatus** (T10) — 40 cm from incisors; lower oesophageal sphincter (LOS) zone

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD)** — LOS incompetence → acid reflux → heartburn; risk: obesity, hiatus hernia, pregnancy
- **Hiatus hernia** — stomach herniates through oesophageal hiatus; sliding (most common, 95%) or rolling (paraesophageal, 5%)
- **Barrett's oesophagus** — metaplasia of squamous → columnar epithelium; complication of chronic GORD; precursor to adenocarcinoma
- **Oesophageal carcinoma** — squamous (upper/mid, risk: smoking + alcohol) vs. adenocarcinoma (lower, risk: GORD + Barrett's)
- **Achalasia** — failure of LOS relaxation + loss of peristalsis; dysphagia to liquids + solids; "bird's beak" on barium swallow; treat: pneumatic dilatation or Heller myotomy
- **Oesophageal varices** — dilated veins at GO junction due to portal hypertension ([[Portal System]]); rupture → massive haematemesis; treat: terlipressin + endoscopic band ligation
- **Mallory-Weiss tear** — mucosal tear at GO junction after forceful vomiting → haematemesis; usually self-limiting
- **Boerhaave syndrome** — full-thickness oesophageal rupture after violent vomiting → surgical emergency; Mackler triad: vomiting + chest pain + surgical emphysema

